Anonymous Sun 07 Feb 2021 06:02:43 No.36143983 Report
Quoted By: >>36144272 >>36145043
>>36143633
The repetition is important, to a certain degree, and usually in dialogue heavy stuff it becomes necessary. Because it's such a basic, well understood and unambiguous word, it blurs and melds into the narrative.
Suddenly, the brain acknowledges the presence, knows it applies a character talking, but it just vanishes. I know writing the word forces you to consider it, but to the reader it clarifies as needed and is smothered by what should be interesting dialogue.

Of course using a little body-language before a spoken sentence can work, even without using said or any other word to describe dialogue.

>She scratched the back of her neck. "I guess it didn't feel natural. No offense meant, though!"
can work just as well as:
>"I guess it didn't feel natural," she said. "No offense meant, though!"
The first confers some additional sense of personality; she's obviously a bit nervous or feels awkward about something that happened, even if the second sentence already pushes that as well.
It is longer, though, since we're adding five extra words, which is why it shouldn't be abused since that just bulks it out and it does get distracting.
